AN ACT relating to crimes; increasing the penalties for a customer who unlawfully
engages in prostitution or solicitation therefor; requiring a peace officer
to make an arrest with or without a warrant under certain
circumstances; revising requirements for the automatic sealing of
records in certain circumstances; revising provisions relating to
certain civil actions involving prostitution and solicitation for
prostitution; and providing other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law prohibits a customer from engaging in prostitution or solicitation for
2 prostitution except in a licensed house of prostitution. Existing law provides that a customer
3 who violates such a prohibition: (1) for a first offense that involves an adult, is guilty of a
4 misdemeanor, punishable by imprisonment in the county jail for not more than 6 months and
5 by a fine of not less than $400 but not more than $1,000; (2) for a subsequent offense that
6 involves an adult, is guilty of a gross misdemeanor, punishable by imprisonment in the county
7 jail for not more than 364 days and by certain minimum fines; and (3) for any offense, is
8 subject to a civil penalty of not less than $200 per offense. Additionally, existing law provides
9 for the automatic sealing of records if a person is discharged and the proceedings against the
10 person are dismissed upon the fulfillment of the terms and conditions of a court-ordered
11 program for the treatment of persons who solicit prostitution. (NRS 201.354)
12 [This] Section 1 of this bill: (1) requires a peace officer to arrest a person if the peace
13 officer has probable cause to believe that the person has violated such a prohibition; (2)
14 increases the minimum fine for a first offense to not less than $800; (3) increases the civil
15 penalty for any offense to $600; and (4) authorizes a person to petition the court 2 years after
16 the person is discharged and the proceedings against the person are dismissed for the sealing
17 of all records relating to the discharge and dismissal.
18 Existing law generally provides that when a person suffers an injury as the
19 proximate result of a wrongful act, the person who caused the injury is liable to the
20 person injured for damages. (NRS 41.130) In general, existing law requires a civil action
21 to recover damages for injuries arising from the wrongful act of another person to be

