22 commenced within 2 years after the date on which the wrongful act occurred. (NRS
23 11.190) Existing law exempts certain civil actions from this requirement, including a civil
24 action to recover damages for sexual exploitation, if the sexual exploitation occurred
25 when the plaintiff was less than 18 years of age. For purposes of this exemption, existing
26 law defines sexual exploitation to include forcing, allowing or encouraging a child to
27 solicit for or engage in prostitution. Therefore, under existing law, a civil action to
28 recover damages for prostitution or solicitation for prostitution may be commenced at
29 any time, if the prostitution or solicitation for prostitution occurred when the plaintiff
30 was less than 18 years of age. (NRS 11.215, 432B.110)
31 Section 1.6 of this bill specifically authorizes a person who has suffered an injury as
32 the proximate result of unlawful prostitution or solicitation for prostitution to bring a
33 civil action to recover damages for injuries arising from the prostitution or solicitation
34 for prostitution against the person convicted of the offense. Section 1.4 of this bill
35 exempts a civil action brought pursuant to section 1.2 from the generally applicable 2-
36 year statute of limitations prescribed by existing law. Section 1.2 of this bill provides that
37 a civil action brought pursuant to section 1.6 must be commenced within 20 years after
38 the date on which the violation occurred, unless an exception applies. Section 1.4
39 exempts a civil action to recover damages for injuries arising from unlawful prostitution
40 or solicitation for prostitution from the 20-year statute of limitations prescribed by
41 section 1.2 if the prostitution or solicitation for prostitution occurred when the plaintiff
42 was less than 18 years of age. Consistent with existing law, any such civil action may be
43 commenced at any time. (NRS 11.215, 432B.110)
